.TH SANITIZE 1 "2026-05-21" "sanitize" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
sanitize \- sanitize strings for safe use as filenames
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sanitize
.RI [ flags ]
.IR text ...
.br
.B sanitize
.B \-f
.RB [ \-n ]
.IR file ...
.br
.B sanitize
.B \-r
.RB [ \-n ]
.IR dir ...
.br
.B san
.RB [ \-rn ]
.IR file | dir ...
.br
.I command
.B |
.B sanitize
.RB [ \-0 ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sanitize
transforms input strings into clean, filesystem-safe names.
It lowercases, strips diacritics, replaces non-alphanumeric characters
with hyphens, deduplicates consecutive hyphens, and trims
leading/trailing non-alphanumeric characters.
Output is restricted to Latin-script characters, digits, and hyphens.
Every output is validated against a strict postcondition before being
returned; if any disallowed character slips through the pipeline, the
tool fails with a diagnostic error rather than producing an unsafe result.
.PP
Multiple arguments are joined with hyphens before processing.
With no arguments and piped input,
.B sanitize
reads one line at a time from stdin and writes one sanitized line per line.
Blank lines and lines that sanitize to empty are skipped.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-file
Rename files instead of sanitizing text.
The filename is split from its extension; each part is sanitized separately.
Will not overwrite existing files.
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-recursive
Recursively rename files and directories in the given directory tree.
Entries are processed depth-first (deepest first) so that renaming
a child does not invalidate a parent path.
Implies
.BR \-f .
Handles SIGINT gracefully, stopping between renames.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-dry\-run
Show what would be renamed without actually renaming.
Implies
.BR \-f .
.TP
.BR \-0 ", " \-\-null
Use null bytes instead of newlines as input/output delimiters.
For use with
.BR find (1)
.B \-print0
and
.BR xargs (1)
.BR \-0 .
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print usage summary and exit.
.PP
Short flags can be combined:
.B \-fn
is equivalent to
.BR "\-f \-n" .
Use
.B \-\-
to separate flags from arguments starting with a hyphen.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Runtime error (rename failed, target already exists, interrupted).
.TP
.B 2
Usage error or postcondition failure (unknown flag, missing arguments,
disallowed character in output).
.SH TRANSFORMATION PIPELINE
Input is processed through the following stages in order:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
removeIllFormed \(-> toLower \(-> removeAccents \(-> replaceNonAlphaNum \(-> dedupHyp \(-> trimEnds \(-> validate
.fi
.RE
.TP
.B removeIllFormed
Replace ill-formed UTF-8 sequences with U+FFFD.
.TP
.B toLower
Lowercase the entire string.
.TP
.B removeAccents
NFD decomposition followed by removal of combining marks (Unicode Mn category).
Characters that don't NFD-decompose are special-cased: Polish \[/l]/L,
German \[ss], Croatian \[d-]/D, Danish/Norwegian \[/o]/O,
ligatures \[ae]/AE and \[oe]/OE, Maltese h/H, Turkish dotless i.
.TP
.B replaceNonAlphaNum
Replace anything outside
.I unicode.Latin
and digits with a hyphen.
.TP
.B dedupHyp
Collapse runs of consecutive hyphens into a single hyphen.
.TP
.B trimEnds
Strip leading/trailing non-Latin, non-digit characters.
.TP
.B validate
Postcondition check: verify the output contains only [a\-z0\-9\-],
with no leading, trailing, or consecutive hyphens.
Returns an error identifying the offending character and its Unicode
codepoint if any disallowed character is present.
.SH EXAMPLES
Sanitize text:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ sanitize "Hello, World!"
hello-world

$ sanitize "Zażółć gęślą jaźń"
zazolc-gesla-jazn

$ sanitize foo bar baz
foo-bar-baz
.fi
.RE
.PP
Read from stdin:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ echo "Café Résumé" | sanitize
cafe-resume
.fi
.RE
.PP
Null-delimited I/O:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ find . \-print0 | sanitize \-0 | xargs \-0 echo
.fi
.RE
.PP
Rename files:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ sanitize \-f "My Document.PDF"
My Document.PDF \(-> my-document.pdf

$ sanitize \-fn *.txt
Report (Final).txt \(-> report-final.txt
.fi
.RE
.PP
Recursive rename with dry run:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ sanitize \-rn ~/Downloads/
.fi
.RE
.PP
Via san symlink:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ san "My File.txt"
My File.txt \(-> my-file.txt
.fi
.RE
.SH SAN SYMLINK
When the binary is invoked as
.BR san ,
file rename mode is enabled automatically without needing
.BR \-f .
To set up:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
ln \-s $(which sanitize) /usr/local/bin/san
.fi
.RE
.SH CAVEATS
The transformation is lossy.
Different input strings can produce identical output.
In file rename mode, this means multiple files in the same directory can
collide (e.g.,
.IR "Café.txt" ,
.IR "cafe!.txt" ,
and
.I "CAFÉ.txt"
all become
.IR "cafe.txt" ).
The tool checks for existing targets before each rename and refuses to
overwrite, but partial renames are possible when processing multiple files.
.PP
Always use
.B \-n
(dry run) first on unfamiliar directories.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR mv (1),
.BR rename (1),
.BR find (1),
.BR xargs (1),
.BR detox (1)
